Most routers (Express, Hono, find-my-way, Rails) return **decoded** params, whereas we were returning encoded params. With this PR, `route-pattern` returns decoded params too.

`.changes` file for this PR copied below 👇

---

Matches return decoded values for params in pathname

```ts
let pattern = new RoutePattern('/posts/:slug')

let url = new URL('https://blog.example.com/posts/💿')
pattern.match(url)?.params.slug
// Before -> '%F0%9F%92%BF'
// After -> '💿'

url = new URL('https://blog.example.com/posts/café-hà-nội')
pattern.match(url)?.params.slug
// Before -> 'caf%C3%A9-h%C3%A0-n%E1%BB%99i'
// After -> 'café-hà-nội'

url = new URL('https://blog.example.com/posts/北京')
pattern.match(url)?.params.slug
// Before -> '%E5%8C%97%E4%BA%AC'
// After -> '北京'

url = new URL('https://blog.example.com/posts/مرحبا')
pattern.match(url)?.params.slug
// Before -> '%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%AD%D8%A8%D8%A7'
// After -> 'مرحبا'
```

If you need percent-encoded text again, use JavaScript's native [`encodeURI`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/encodeURI):

```ts
let url = new URL('https://blog.example.com/posts/💿')
let slug = pattern.match(url)!.params.slug
// -> 💿

encodeURI(slug)
// -> '%F0%9F%92%BF'
```

## Perf Benchmarks

`TrieMatcher` performance seems to be unchanged (within expected variance), though this feature did slow down `ArrayMatcher` enough that **now `TrieMatcher` is faster than `ArrayMatcher` for all `matching` benchmarks**:

<img width="843" height="1138" alt="Screenshot 2026-03-23 at 9 59 40 PM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/bd283562-5e27-437a-aa87-cfb7ecb97e34" />

BREAKING CHANGE: Make search param pattern decoding and serialization consistent with `URLSearchParams`. Affects: `RoutePattern.{match,href,search,ast.search}`

Previously, `RoutePattern` treated `?q` and `?q=` as **different** constraints:

```ts
// Before: `?q` and `?q=` are different

let url = new URL('https://example.com?q')

// Matches "key only" constraint?
new RoutePattern('?q').match(url) // ✅ match

// Matches "key and value" constraint?
new RoutePattern('?q=').match(url) // ❌ no match (`null`)

// Different constraints serialized to different strings
new RoutePattern('?q').search // -> 'q'
new RoutePattern('?q=').search // -> 'q='
```

There were two main problems with that approach:

**Unintuitive matching**

```ts
// URL search looks like `?q=`
let url = new URL('https://example.com?q=')

// Pattern search looks like `?q=`
let pattern = new RoutePattern('?q=')

// But "key and value" constraint doesn't match!
pattern.match(url) // ❌ no match (`null`)
```


**Parsing and serialization**

For consistency with `URLSearchParams`, search param patterns should be parsed according to the [WHATWG `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` parsing spec](https://url.spec.whatwg.org/#application/x-www-form-urlencoded-parsing) and should also [encode spaces as `+`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/URLSearchParams#percent_encoding).

Now, we use `URLSearchParams` to parse search param patterns to guarantee decodings are consistent:

```ts
let url = new URL('https://example.com?q=a+b')
// Decodes `+` to ` `
url.searchParams.getAll('q') // -> ['a b']

// Before
let pattern = new RoutePattern('?q=a+b')
// Does not decode `+` to ` `
pattern.ast.search.get('q') // -> ❌ Set { 'a+b' }

// After
let pattern = new RoutePattern('?q=a+b')
// Decodes `+` to ` `
pattern.ast.search.get('q') // -> ✅ Set { 'a b' }
```

Similarly, now that `?q` and `?q=` are semantically equivalent, they should serialize to the same thing:

```ts
new URLSearchParams('q=').toString() // 'q='

// Before
new RoutePattern('?q=').search // ❌ 'q'

// After
new RoutePattern('?q=').search // ✅ 'q='
```

As a result, `RoutePattern`s can no longer represent a "key and any value" constraint.
In practice, this was a niche use-case so we chose correctness and consistency with `URLSearchParams`.
If the need for "key and any value" constraints arises, we can later introduce a separate syntax for that without the unintuitive shortcoming of `?q=`.

With "key and any value" constraints removed, the `missing-search-param` error type thrown by `RoutePattern.href` was made obsolete and was removed.

This PR introduces a shipped `app-skills/` set aimed at people building Remix apps, separate from maintainer-only repo workflow skills.

- Adds a `scaffold-remix-app` skill that sets up a root controller/layout/page, router wiring, Node server boot via `tsx`, and an app-scoped test fixture.
- Adds an `add-sqlite-database` skill for wiring SQLite in `data/db.sqlite` with `lib/db.ts` exporting `db` from `remix/data-table`.
- Adds a `new-route` skill for extending route maps and handlers in a consistent style.

```tsx
export default {
  middleware: [],
  actions: {
    home() {
      return render(
        <Layout>
          <title>My Remix App</title>
          <HomePage />
        </Layout>,
      )
    },
  },
} satisfies Controller<typeof routes.root>
```

This hard-cuts the unreleased `remix/auth` package away from request-handler factories and into four small primitives. It also shrinks `completeAuth()` down to the session-boundary step it actually owns: rotate the session id and hand the session back to the route.

The demos and docs now show route-owned redirects and session writes directly, with module-scope external providers in the social auth demo.

- replaces `createCredentialsAuthLoginRequestHandler()`, `createExternalAuthLoginRequestHandler()`, and `createExternalAuthCallbackRequestHandler()` with `verifyCredentials()`, `startExternalAuth()`, `finishExternalAuth()`, and `completeAuth(context)`
- removes the old request-handler implementation files and rewrites the auth package tests around the new primitives
- updates the social auth demo to use a boot-time provider registry and per-provider controllers, and adds an end-to-end external auth test
- updates the bookstore demo and package READMEs to show inline session writes and direct `Session` imports from Remix

```ts
// Before
router.post(
  routes.auth.session.login.action,
  createCredentialsAuthLoginRequestHandler(passwordProvider, {
    writeSession(session, user) {
      session.set('auth', { userId: user.id })
    },
    successRedirectTo: routes.app.dashboard.href(),
  }),
)
```

```ts
// After
router.post(routes.auth.session.login.action, async (context) => {
  let user = await verifyCredentials(passwordProvider, context)
  if (user == null) {
    return redirect(routes.auth.session.login.index.href())
  }

  let session = completeAuth(context)
  session.set('auth', { userId: user.id })

  return redirect(routes.app.dashboard.href())
})
```

```ts
// External auth after the cutover
let googleProvider = createGoogleAuthProvider({
  clientId: env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID,
  clientSecret: env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET,
  redirectUri: new URL(routes.auth.google.callback.href(), env.APP_ORIGIN),
})

router.get(routes.auth.google.login, (context) =>
  startExternalAuth(googleProvider, context, {
    returnTo: context.url.searchParams.get('returnTo'),
  }),
)

router.get(routes.auth.google.callback, async (context) => {
  let { result, returnTo } = await finishExternalAuth(googleProvider, context)
  let user = await users.upsertFromGoogle(result.profile)

  let session = completeAuth(context)
  session.set('auth', { userId: user.id })

  return redirect(returnTo ?? routes.app.dashboard.href())
})
```

This adds typed request-context contracts to `fetch-router` and the middleware packages that build on it, while keeping the existing controller/action authoring model.

- threads typed request context through `Router`, `RequestContext`, `Controller`, and `BuildAction`
- adds app-facing context helpers in `fetch-router`, including `MiddlewareContext`, `WithParams`, `MergeContext`, and `AnyParams`
- adds `WithAuth` and `WithRequiredAuth` in `auth-middleware` so protected handlers can use `context.get(Auth)` directly
- makes `getContext()` from `async-context-middleware` app-typed via module augmentation
- updates the `social-auth` and `bookstore` demos to use app-local context contracts

```ts
import { Auth, requireAuth, type WithRequiredAuth } from 'remix/auth-middleware'
import { type BuildAction, type RequestContext, type WithParams } from 'remix/fetch-router'
import { route } from 'remix/fetch-router/routes'

let routes = route({
  account: '/account',
})

type AppContext<params extends Record<string, string> = {}> = WithParams<RequestContext, params>

type AuthIdentity = { id: string }

type AuthenticatedAppContext<params extends Record<string, string> = {}> = WithRequiredAuth<
  AppContext<params>,
  AuthIdentity
>

let accountAction = {
  middleware: [requireAuth<AuthIdentity>()],
  handler(context) {
    // AuthenticatedAppContext guarantees good auth here, so identity is available directly.
    let auth = context.get(Auth)
    return Response.json({ id: auth.identity.id })
  },
} satisfies BuildAction<'GET', typeof routes.account, AuthenticatedAppContext>
```

Apps using `async-context-middleware` can also recover their app-specific request context from `getContext()`:

```ts
declare module 'remix/async-context-middleware' {
  interface AsyncContextTypes {
    requestContext: AppContext<AnyParams>
  }
}
```

Another change in this PR is renaming the action-object request handler property from `action` to `handler`.

```ts
// Before
router.get(routes.account, {
  middleware: [requireAuth()],
  action: accountAction.handler,
})
```

```ts
// After
router.get(routes.account, {
  middleware: [requireAuth()],
  handler: accountAction.handler,
})
```

Add first-party auth packages to Remix for browser login flows and request-time authentication.

- adds `remix/auth-middleware` with `auth()`, `requireAuth()`, `createSessionAuthScheme()`, `createBearerTokenAuthScheme()`, and `createAPIAuthScheme()`
- adds `remix/auth` with separate request handlers for credentials and external auth:
  - `createCredentialsAuthLoginRequestHandler()`
  - `createExternalAuthLoginRequestHandler()`
  - `createExternalAuthCallbackRequestHandler()`
- adds generic OIDC plus built-in providers for Google, Microsoft, Okta, Auth0, GitHub, Facebook, and X
- updates the bookstore demo to use the new auth stack for its session-backed flows
- documents the package boundary between login/session writing and request-time auth resolution

```ts
import { createRouter } from 'remix/fetch-router'
import { auth, Auth, createSessionAuthScheme, requireAuth } from 'remix/auth-middleware'
import type { GoodAuth } from 'remix/auth-middleware'
import {
  createCredentialsAuthLoginRequestHandler,
  createCredentialsAuthProvider,
  createExternalAuthCallbackRequestHandler,
  createExternalAuthLoginRequestHandler,
  createGoogleAuthProvider,
} from 'remix/auth'
import { FormData, formData } from 'remix/form-data-middleware'
import { session } from 'remix/session-middleware'

let googleProvider = createGoogleAuthProvider({
  clientId: env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID,
  clientSecret: env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET,
  redirectUri: new URL('/auth/google/callback', env.APP_ORIGIN),
})

let passwordProvider = createCredentialsAuthProvider({
  parse(context) {
    let formData = context.get(FormData)
    return {
      email: String(formData.get('email') ?? ''),
      password: String(formData.get('password') ?? ''),
    }
  },
  verify({ email, password }) {
    return users.verifyPassword(email, password)
  },
})

let router = createRouter({
  middleware: [
    session(sessionCookie, sessionStorage),
    formData(),
    auth({
      schemes: [
        createSessionAuthScheme({
          read(session) {
            return session.get('auth') as { userId: string } | null
          },
          verify(value) {
            return users.getById(value.userId)
          },
        }),
      ],
    }),
  ],
})

router.post(
  '/login',
  createCredentialsAuthLoginRequestHandler(passwordProvider, {
    async writeSession(session, user) {
      session.set('auth', { userId: user.id })
    },
  }),
)

router.get('/login/google', createExternalAuthLoginRequestHandler(googleProvider))
router.get(
  '/auth/google/callback',
  createExternalAuthCallbackRequestHandler(googleProvider, {
    async writeSession(session, result) {
      let user = await users.upsertFromGoogle(result.profile)
      session.set('auth', { userId: user.id })
    },
  }),
)

router.get('/dashboard', {
  middleware: [requireAuth()],
  action(context) {
    let auth = context.get(Auth) as GoodAuth<{ id: string; email: string | null }>
    return Response.json(auth.identity)
  },
})
```

This refactors `data-table` around reusable `Query` objects and an overloaded `db.exec(...)` API.

Instead of exposing a public `QueryBuilder` type that is always bound to a database, the package now exposes `Query` and `query(table)` for building immutable unbound queries. `db.query(table)` stays available as shorthand, but it now returns the same bound `Query` class.

- replace the public `QueryBuilder` export with `Query` and `query(table)`
- extend `db.exec(...)` to execute unbound queries and immutable read/write command objects in addition to raw SQL
- keep `db.query(table)` ergonomics while aligning it with the same `Query` type and execution model
- update release notes, docs, and runtime/type-safety coverage for both bound and unbound flows

```ts
import { createDatabase, query } from 'remix/data-table'

let db = createDatabase(adapter)

let activeUsers = await db.exec(
  query(users).where({ status: 'active' }).orderBy('id', 'asc'),
)

let count = await db.exec(query(users).where({ status: 'active' }).count())
await db.exec(query(users).where({ status: 'pending' }).update({ status: 'active' }))
```

```ts
// Before
import { QueryBuilder } from 'remix/data-table'

let rows = await db.query(users).where({ status: 'active' }).all()
```

```ts
// After
import { Query, query } from 'remix/data-table'

let rows = await db.exec(query(users).where({ status: 'active' }))
let sameRows = await db.query(users).where({ status: 'active' }).all()
```

This updates the bookstore demo to stop augmenting `RequestContext` with a custom `db` property. Instead, the demo now stores the database on request context with `Database` as the key and reads it back with `get(Database)`, matching the same pattern already used for `Session` and `FormData`.

That keeps the demo's request-context story consistent and removes the separate module-augmentation escape hatch from the example app.

- replace `context.db = db` with `context.set(Database, db)` in the bookstore database middleware
- update request-scoped handlers and middleware to read the database with `get(Database)`
- remove the bookstore-specific `RequestContext` augmentation file
- update the bookstore README to describe the actual request-context pattern used by the demo

```ts
// Before
import type { Database } from 'remix/data-table'

declare module 'remix/fetch-router' {
  interface RequestContext {
    db: Database
  }
}

async function action({ db, get }: RequestContext) {
  let session = get(Session)
  return db.find(users, session.get('userId'))
}
```

```ts
// After
import { Database } from 'remix/data-table'

async function action({ get }: RequestContext) {
  let db = get(Database)
  let session = get(Session)
  return db.find(users, session.get('userId'))
}
```

This PR adds a new `router.crawl()` API to fetch-router that enables first-class crawling/spidering of the application served by the router - enabling very easy pre-rendering (basically a built-in `wget`).  If we don't want to bloat the `router` API area we could also easily pull this into a `import { crawl } from 'remix/fetch-router/crawl'` sub-export.

The spidering logic is implemented with a minimal custom parser and benchmarked against [node-html-parser](https://www.npmjs.com/package/node-html-parser) via `pnpm i; cd packages/fetch-router/bench; pnpm bench`.  It's currently around 2-3x faster because it only implemented the the minimal capabilities needed to extract link/asset paths from a document.

I've concerted our docs generation to use this new API if you want to see it in action (`pnpm i; cd docs; pnpm run docs; pnpm prerender`), but API looks like this:

```ts
interface CrawlOpts {
  // paths to crawl (default ['/'])
  paths?: string[],
  // traverse outbound links (default true)
  spider?: boolean, 
  // filter paths to crawl (defaults to non-absolute paths)
  filter(href): boolean, 
  // URL variants to crawl that may not show up as outbound links
  variants?: (path) => Promise<string[]>,
};

for await (let { pathname, filepath, response } of router.crawl()) {
  await writeResponse(filepath, response);
  console.log(`Write path ${pathname} to file ${filepath}`);
}
```

This PR simplifies request-scoped application storage in `@remix-run/fetch-router` by moving storage methods directly onto `RequestContext`.

- Remove `context.storage` and the `AppStorage` export
- Add `context.get(key)`, `context.set(key, value)`, and `context.has(key)` as the request-scoped storage API
- Keep `createStorageKey(...)` and update fetch-router docs/tests around the new context API

This keeps the storage API type-safe while removing an extra object layer from the request context shape.

```ts
import { createStorageKey } from 'remix/fetch-router'

let userKey = createStorageKey<{ id: string }>()

// Before
router.get('/posts/:id', ({ storage }) => {
  storage.set(userKey, currentUser)
  let user = storage.get(userKey)
  return Response.json(user)
})

// After
router.get('/posts/:id', ({ set, get }) => {
  set(userKey, currentUser)
  let user = get(userKey)
  return Response.json(user)
})
```

This simplifies `fetch-router` controller mapping by enforcing a single controller shape for route maps: `{ actions, middleware? }`.

- Removes the dual controller API ("with middleware" vs "without middleware") for `router.map(routeMap, controller)`
- Simplifies the `router.map()` runtime implementation by using one recursive controller path
- Updates `fetch-router` tests, docs, and demos to the new contract
- Adds a `minor` breaking change file for `@remix-run/fetch-router` (`BREAKING CHANGE:` + migration guidance)

This makes route-map controllers more explicit and consistent at every level of nesting, and removes ambiguity in both types and runtime behavior.

```ts
// Before
router.map(routes, {
  home() {
    return new Response('Home')
  },
  blog: {
    index() {
      return new Response('Blog')
    },
  },
})
```

```ts
// After
router.map(routes, {
  actions: {
    home() {
      return new Response('Home')
    },
    blog: {
      actions: {
        index() {
          return new Response('Blog')
        },
      },
    },
  },
})
```

Switching a host node from text children to `innerHTML` could dispatch a `NotFoundError` through the root `error` event even though the DOM ended up in the expected final state.

- Adds a regression test for `<div>text</div> -> <div innerHTML="..." />` transitions
- Verifies the update does not emit root `error` events
- Makes text-node removal idempotent when the node was already detached by an earlier `innerHTML` update

```tsx
let renderError: unknown
root.addEventListener('error', (event) => {
  renderError = (event as ErrorEvent).error
})

root.render(<div>From text child</div>)
root.render(<div innerHTML="<span>From innerHTML</span>" />)

expect(renderError).toBeUndefined()
```

```ts
// before
if (isCommittedTextNode(node)) {
  domParent.removeChild(node._dom)
}

// after
if (isCommittedTextNode(node)) {
  node._dom.parentNode?.removeChild(node._dom)
}
```

`createRangeRoot` requires the start and end boundary nodes to share the same parent, but the existing invariant never actually validated that condition. It compared `end.parentNode` to a local variable assigned from `end.parentNode`, so the check was always true.

- Adds a regression test that builds split-parent boundaries and asserts `createRangeRoot` throws
- Fixes the invariant to validate `start.parentNode === end.parentNode`
- Keeps the change scoped to boundary validation behavior only

```ts
// regression test
let containerA = document.createElement('div')
let containerB = document.createElement('div')
let start = document.createComment('start')
let end = document.createComment('end')
containerA.appendChild(start)
containerB.appendChild(end)

expect(() => createRangeRoot([start, end])).toThrow('Boundaries must share parent')
```

```ts
// fix
let container = end.parentNode
invariant(container, 'Expected parent node')
invariant(start.parentNode === container, 'Boundaries must share parent')
```

## Summary

This PR introduces host element mixins to `@remix-run/component` and removes legacy interaction pathways.

- Adds the new host `mix` composition model and core authoring APIs: `createMixin`, `MixinDescriptor`, `MixinHandle`, `MixinType`, and `MixValue`
- Adds built-in mixins and helpers for common behavior:
  - `on(...)`, `ref(...)`, `css(...)`
  - `pressEvents(...)`, `keysEvents(...)`
  - `animateEntrance(...)`, `animateExit(...)`, `animateLayout(...)`
- Migrates component internals, tests, docs, and demos to mixin usage
- Removes legacy host prop runtime support (`on`, `css`, `animate`, `connect`) in favor of mixins
- Removes `@remix-run/interaction` and corresponding `remix` interaction re-exports, with migration to component-native APIs like `addEventListeners(...)`

This branch also includes broad app/demo migrations (`docs`, `bookstore`, `frames`, `sse`) and test/CI updates related to the new runtime behavior and coverage expectations.

## Composition Example

Styles, interactions, and animation behaviors compose on a single element via `mix`:

```tsx
import {
  animateEntrance,
  animateExit,
  css,
  on,
  pressEvents,
  spring,
  type Handle,
} from "@remix-run/component";

let baseButton = css({
  padding: "10px 14px",
  borderRadius: "8px",
  border: "1px solid transparent",
  fontWeight: 600,
  cursor: "pointer",
});

let primaryButton = css({
  backgroundColor: "#3b82f6",
  color: "white",
  "&:hover": { backgroundColor: "#2563eb" },
  "&:active": { transform: "translateY(1px)" },
});

function SaveButton(handle: Handle) {
  let isPressed = false;

  return () => (
    <button
      mix={[
        baseButton,
        primaryButton,
        css({ transition: `transform ${spring()}` }),
        pressEvents(),
        on(pressEvents.down, () => {
          isPressed = true;
          handle.update();
        }),
        on(pressEvents.up, () => {
          isPressed = false;
          handle.update();
        }),
        animateEntrance({
          opacity: 0,
          transform: "translateY(8px) scale(0.98)",
          ...spring("bouncy"),
        }),
        animateExit({
          opacity: 0,
          transform: "translateY(-6px) scale(0.98)",
          ...spring("snappy"),
        }),
      ]}
      style={{ transform: isPressed ? "scale(0.98)" : undefined }}
    >
      Save
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Breaking Changes

- `@remix-run/component` host `on` prop removed
  - Old: `<button on={{ click() {} }} />`
  - New: `<button mix={[on('click', () => {})]} />`
- `@remix-run/component` host `css` prop runtime removed
  - Old: `<div css={{ color: 'red' }} />`
  - New: `<div mix={[css({ color: 'red' })]} />`
- `@remix-run/component` host `animate` prop runtime removed
  - Old: `<div animate={{ enter: true, exit: true, layout: true }} />`
  - New: `<div mix={[animateEntrance(), animateExit(), animateLayout()]} />`
- `@remix-run/component` host `connect` prop removed
  - Old: `<div connect={(node, signal) => {}} />`
  - New: `<div mix={[ref((node, signal) => {})]} />`
- `@remix-run/interaction` package removed
  - Migrate to `@remix-run/component` APIs (`createMixin`, `on`, `addEventListeners`, `TypedEventTarget`)

## Migration Notes

- Replace host props with `mix={[...]}`
- Replace `handle.on(...)` usage with `addEventListeners(target, handle.signal, listeners)`
- Replace custom interaction definitions with `createMixin(...)` + typed custom events
- Update imports from `@remix-run/interaction` / `remix/interaction/*` to component exports

This PR lands the `data-table` migration system and completes the operation-model split across core + adapters.

## What this includes

- Adds first-class migrations under `remix/data-table/migrations`:
  - `createMigration(...)`
  - chainable `column` API (`import { column as c }`)
  - split migration handles in callbacks:
    - `db` for immediate DML/data operations
    - `schema` for migration DDL/planning operations
  - registry + runner + optional Node migration loader
- Finalizes operation naming split:
  - `DataManipulationOperation`
  - `DataMigrationOperation`
- Updates postgres/mysql/sqlite adapters to compile + execute migration operations
- Renames top-level table-definition API from `createTable(...)` to `table(...)`
- Adds table lifecycle hooks (`beforeWrite`, `afterWrite`, `beforeDelete`, `afterDelete`, `afterRead`) and table-level `validate(...)`
- Expands JSDocs, README docs, and adapter/core coverage

## Migration File Example

```ts
import { column as c, table } from 'remix/data-table'
import { createMigration } from 'remix/data-table/migrations'

let accounts = table({
  name: 'accounts',
  columns: {
    id: c.integer().primaryKey(),
  },
})

let users = table({
  name: 'users',
  columns: {
    id: c.integer().primaryKey(),
    account_id: c.integer().notNull(),
    email: c.varchar(255).notNull().unique(),
    created_at: c.timestamp({ withTimezone: true }).defaultNow(),
  },
})

export default createMigration({
  async up({ db, schema }) {
    await schema.createTable(accounts)
    await schema.createTable(users)

    await schema.createIndex(users, 'email', { unique: true })

    await schema.alterTable(users, table => {
      table.addForeignKey('account_id', accounts, 'id')
      table.addCheck("email like '%@%'")
      table.addIndex(['account_id', 'email'])
    })

    if (db.adapter.dialect === 'sqlite') {
      await db.exec('pragma foreign_keys = on')
    }

    await schema.plan(`update users set created_at = now() where created_at is null`)
  },

  async down({ schema }) {
    await schema.dropTable(users, { ifExists: true })
    await schema.dropTable(accounts, { ifExists: true })
  },
})
```

Notes:

- Methods that take a table accept either a table name string (`'app.users'`) or a `table(...)` object.
- Key/index columns accept both single and compound forms (`'id'` or `['tenant_id', 'id']`).
- Constraint/index names are optional; when omitted, `data-table` generates deterministic names.

## Lifecycle Callback Example

```ts
import { column as c, fail, table } from 'remix/data-table'

let users = table({
  name: 'users',
  columns: {
    id: c.integer().primaryKey(),
    email: c.varchar(255).notNull(),
    role: c.enum(['customer', 'admin']).notNull(),
    created_at: c.timestamp({ withTimezone: true }).defaultNow(),
  },

  beforeWrite({ value }) {
    if (typeof value.email === 'string') {
      return {
        value: {
          ...value,
          email: value.email.trim().toLowerCase(),
        },
      }
    }

    return { value }
  },

  validate({ operation, value }) {
    if (operation === 'create' && typeof value.email !== 'string') {
      return fail('Email is required.', ['email'])
    }

    return { value }
  },

  afterWrite({ operation, affectedRows }) {
    console.log('users', operation, 'affected rows:', affectedRows)
  },

  beforeDelete({ where }) {
    if (where.length === 0) {
      return fail('Refusing to delete all users at once.')
    }
  },

  afterRead({ value }) {
    return {
      value: {
        ...value,
        email: typeof value.email === 'string' ? value.email.toLowerCase() : value.email,
      },
    }
  },
})
```

## Runner Example

```ts
import path from 'node:path'
import { Pool } from 'pg'
import { createPostgresDatabaseAdapter } from 'remix/data-table-postgres'
import { createMigrationRunner } from 'remix/data-table/migrations'
import { loadMigrations } from 'remix/data-table/migrations/node'

let pool = new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL })
let adapter = createPostgresDatabaseAdapter(pool)
let migrations = await loadMigrations(path.resolve('app/db/migrations'))
let runner = createMigrationRunner(adapter, migrations)

await runner.up()
```

## Runtime Semantics

- `dryRun: true` compiles and returns SQL without applying changes.
- In `dryRun`, `schema.hasTable(...)` and `schema.hasColumn(...)` read live database state (no in-memory simulation of pending dry-run operations).
- When migration transactions are enabled, migration-time DDL (`schema.createTable(...)`, etc.), DML (`db.exec(...)` / query builder), and introspection all run in the same adapter transaction context.

